Parts/Description/adapter_1v_bullet_meth: Adding nosecones is an aerodynamic breeze with the NCS Adapter. Take advantage of that hollow space to sneak in a little more fuel!
Parts/Description/adapter_1v_cir-sqr: When is a square not a square? When it’s round, of course. OK, that didn’t really make sense, but the CSTA-125 Truss adapter certainly does. Perfect for all your truss adaptation needs.
Parts/Description/adapter_1v_conical_0v-: When drag is more a problem than mass, use the FL-A10 adapter to change part sizes. Totally not a scrapped command pod design.
Parts/Description/adapter_1v_flat_0v-1v: Taking inspiration from his dinner plate, Jebediah designed the FL-A5 with two differently-sized connection points. This adapter is as aerodynamically sound as its inspiration.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_2point_1v-2: The TVR-200L splits a single large body into two smaller bodies. Perfect when you want to double up on those sweet stack decoupler explosions.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_3point_1v-2: The TVR-300L splits a single large body into three smaller bodies. Use for those times you want to see three smaller explosions instead of one large explosion.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_4point_1v-2: The TVR-400L splits a single large body into four small bodies. Useful for adding expensive table legs.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_cir-sqr: It’s said the key to success is the ability to adapt. The CSTA-250 allows you to do just that, adapt. Adaptation only for square truss to circular truss.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_conical_1v-: This adapter will connect Rockomax parts with obviously smaller, weaker parts. Warranty is void when connected to non-Rockomax parts.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_conical_met: The RS-AD 800 was designed, quite frankly, because almost every other size adaptor was already available. So C7 seized the opportunity to add one more to their inventory before anyone else did.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_flat_1v-2v: While Rockomax cannot condone the use of non-Rockomax parts, this adapter will allow connections with smaller parts without dramatically affecting height.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_m2_1x1_meth: Is it a spaceplane? Is it a rocket? With the RF-AD 400 fueled adapter, why not have both?
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_m2_1x2_meth: Use the RF-AD 800 when you want spaceplane business in the front and a rocket party way, way in the back. The fuel storage is an added bonus.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_m2_2point_m: The RF-AD-B 400 bicoupler has two connections in the back for engines, intakes, or Kerbals with very wide legs. The straight sides are ideal wing attachment points.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_m2_methalox: The RF-AD-L 800 provides a seamless transition between C7's Mk2 suite of parts and any medium sized rocket part while pulling double duty as a fuel tank.
Parts/Description/adapter_2v_rightcone_m: The RS-AD-SL 800 was the last winner of C7's "Make a Covert Fuel Tank" contest, serving as adapter, slide, and Rockomax adapter imposter.
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_cir-sqr: The CSTA-375 is a large circular to square truss adapter. That’s all we’ve got, sorry. The writers are at a conference… again.
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_conical_2v-: The ADP-ML-C is the conical version of the flatter Medium to Large adapter. Add a little flair to your size transitions.
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_m3_conical_: The RF-AD 2500 connects Mk3 parts to medium rocket parts and holds fuel. Is it pointy or curvy? Yes.
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_m3_methalox: The RF-AD-XL 2500 is a fueled adapter that connects Mk3 parts to large rocket parts, for those family-sized trips. Hope you packed some games!
The RF-AD 2000 fueled adapter is for those who love the old time feel of the Mk2 suite but love the power of the Mk3 suite. We also rent it out for children's parties.
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_m3_rightcon: The RF-AD-SL 2500 fueled adapter is the significantly slantier cousin of the RF-AD 2500. Remember: slanting is for subassemblies!
Parts/Description/adapter_3v_methalox_2v: The Kerbodyne ADTP-2-3 fueled adapter is very similar to C7 Aerospace's RF-AD 800. Kerbodyne insists their adapter is far superior, but they say their reports were eaten.
Parts/Description/adapter_4v_3v-4v: Got a little body and a big, big engine? The ADP-LXL will seamlessly connect those parts in a minimal profile.
Parts/Description/adapter_4v_cir-sqr: Sometimes a square truss needs to be more circular, and a circular truss needs to be more square. That’s where the CSTA-500 Truss Adapter comes in. Strong, lightweight, and just fun to look at!
Parts/Description/adapter_4v_methalox_3v: The ADTP-3-4 is a large, fueled adaptor and the pet project of the Kerbodyne CEO. It is designed specifically for those that refuse to have one empty millimeter of space on their craft.
Parts/Description/antenna_0v_16: The Communotron 16 is Ionic Symphonic Protonic Electronics’ first attempt to send beautiful music (or boring dialog) streaming across the airwaves. 300 page instruction manual included free of charge.
Parts/Description/antenna_0v_16s: The Communotron 16-S is a variation of the popular Comm-16 antenna, designed for aircraft and rovers. It is very streamlined, perfect for certain individuals (Jeb) that refuse to follow our safe speed antenna guidelines (included with every purchase).
Parts/Description/antenna_0v_dish_ra-15:
The RA-15 is a small, static antenna, good for long chats with Mission Control and sledding on Minmus.
 (Note: Mission Control does NOT sanction Minmus sledding while on duty)
Parts/Description/antenna_0v_dish_ra-2: The RA-2 is a small, static antenna designed mostly for communication probes, but it can serve in a multitude of roles. It can even work as a small bathtub if the need arises.
Parts/Description/antenna_1v_dish_88-88: The Communotron 88-88 is a high-gain antenna designed to handle the stress of take-off and re-entry. That strength is partly due to its patented parabolic folding design, which our research team maintains was not inspired by an umbrella.
Parts/Description/antenna_1v_dish_hg5: The HG-5 is a best-selling antenna that can transmit your messages clearly across vast distances of space. It is also fully retractable, so you don’t accidentally rip one off in an atmosphere - assuming you remember to retract it.
Parts/Description/antenna_1v_dish_hg55: The Communotron HG-55 is a stunningly fast direct communication antenna, originally designed for deep space probes and other craft. When you absolutely have to have the latest sports scores, this is the antenna for you.
Parts/Description/antenna_1v_dish_ra-100: The RA-100 was originally designed to broadcast entire symphonies to the stars, but it was reluctantly modified by Ionic Symphonic engineers to transmit and receive science reports and other dull spoken messages as well.
Parts/Description/antenna_1v_parabolic_d: The Communotron DTS-M1 is a fully deployable data transmission system designed to have a minimal flight profile while retracted. Occasional tweaking, and a good swift kick, may be required for optimal performance.
Parts/Description/attachpoint_1v_radial: When R&D reverse engineered a defective docking port found behind the Clamp-O-Tron factory, they not only discovered why it would never let go, they were able to use this to their advantage. The result is the BZ-52. Now you can attach just about anything you want wherever you want.
Parts/Description/booster_0v_solid_sepra: The Sepratron-1 is a miniature SRB designed to safely propel side-mounted boosters from a rocket during decoupling. Laughing in the face of its competition, this highly successful mini-booster defines Periapsis RSC’s slogan: “Build just one thing, and build it great”.
Parts/Description/booster_1v_solid_flea: The RT-5 “Flea” is the smallest solid rocket booster available. It was originally designed to be the largest firecracker in the world, but one of the end caps blew off, and it shot 1000 meters straight up. The KSC engineers knew they were onto something good.
Parts/Description/booster_1v_solid_hamme: The “Hammer" is a small but powerful solid rocket booster. It can be used as an individual stage, and it works quite well when two or more are radially attached to a craft as side boosters. Yes, it may be essentially two “Flea” SRB’s stacked atop each other, what’s your point?
Parts/Description/booster_1v_solid_kickb: The SRB-KD25k is one of Kerbodyne's largest solid rocket boosters. In a blatant attempt to out do Rockomax, the “Kickback” has well over twice the fuel and thrust as the “Thumper”. These are not cheap to build, so try to recover them in one piece.
Parts/Description/booster_1v_solid_thump: Rockomax’s “Thumper” is solid rocket booster built to do one job well. It has no thrust vectoring, and it cannot be shut off. It is meant for one thing and one thing only: more power!
Parts/Description/booster_2v_solid_clyde: When you need sheer power on the launch pad, use the S2-33. This massive solid rocket booster provides a staggering amount of thrust and features some limited gimbling. Once ignited there is no turning back, so strap in and enjoy the ride.
Parts/Description/cabin_1v_m1_crew: From small transports to private jets, the Mk1 “Stowaway” crew cabin is designed for both style and comfort. It even includes a small refrigerated storage compartment for all your in-flight snack needs.
Parts/Description/cabin_2v_crew_hitchhik: Late one night, Jebediah Kerman Sr. decided to take his family on a vacation to space. The next day, he welded 4 lawn chairs inside an empty fuel tank, added a couple windows, and cut an escape hatch. Now the PPD-10 “Hitchhiker” is a best selling crew cabin for Jeb’s Junkyard.
Parts/Description/cabin_2v_m2_crew: The Mk2 Crew Cabin, affectionately named the “Tag Along," is a state of the art 4 seat crew cabin built for high-speed jets and SSTOs. Air discomfort bags sold separately.
Parts/Description/cabin_3v_crew: Originally two “Hitchhiker” crew cabins welded together, the PPD-20 was named the “Wayfarer.” It has additional storage compartments for snacks, board games, stuffed toys, and a variety of other fun items to keep your crew happy during their flight.
Parts/Description/cabin_3v_m3_crew: Sit down, buckle up, and prepare to travel in style in the Mk3 “Skybus” 16 seat passenger cabin. This spacious compartment contains everything a Kerbal could wish for, including an extensive library of in-flight movies. No fighting for a window seat, please.
Parts/Description/cargobay_1v_1x1: The CBS-125 is a small but sturdy cargo hold for your craft. It is guaranteed to keep everything from delicate science equipment to yummy snacks safe and secure.
Parts/Description/cargobay_1v_1x8: With the success of their CBS-125, Sean’s Cannery introduced the CBL-125 long cargo hold, because cargo doesn't complain about being cramped.
Parts/Description/cargobay_2v_1x1: The CBS-250 was designed after several lengthy discussion with C7 aerospace to build round cargo holds proved futile. While C7 held onto its aesthetics, Sean's Cannery developed an everyman's cargo bay.
Parts/Description/cargobay_2v_1x8: The CBL-250 long cargo hold is built to hold anything that does not need to breathe. There are passenger modules available for your crew. Sean’s cannery not responsible for stowaway incidents.
Parts/Description/cargobay_2v_m2_1x1: Why build a space plane if you can't bring along snacks? With this in mind, the engineers at C7 designed the Mk2 CRG-S Cargo Bay, guaranteed to keep your snacks and other inferior cargo safe and secure.
Parts/Description/cargobay_2v_m2_1x2: As the need for more and more resources grew, the engineers at C7 responded with the Mk2 CRG Cargo bay. Now with twice the capacity of the CRG-S, for all your snack needs. Can also hold satellites and other non-snack items.
Parts/Description/cargobay_2v_nose: After weeks of intensive R&D meetings, a young intern at Sean’s Cannery made a remarkable observation. Why are rocket nosecones empty? Despite its unconventional cargo hold, the CN-250 Cargo Nose is just as capable of hauling what you need.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_1x1: The CBS-375 can hold parts, fuel tanks, and treats. Ever have a desire to haul 300 tons of Sean’s deluxe mint ice-cream to Minmus?
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_1x8: The CBL-375 is a large cargo bay designed to haul large cargo. Marketing couldn’t come up with anything else to say except to buy one today.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_m3_1x1: When the bathrooms had to be closed to store a surplus of JFT-2500 fuel tanks, the team at C7 came up with the brilliant idea of slicing them up, adding a couple hinges, and repurposing them into cargo bays! Rumors that the CEO took all the credit are totally false and not to be believed.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_m3_1x2: The Mk3 CRG is the standard cargo bay for most larger aircraft and shuttles in use today. These impressive containers can pack a huge amount of resources, smaller craft, or whatever you may need to transport around. And snacks, don’t forget to pack lots of snacks.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_m3_1x4: For those that need only the largest, most outrageous aircraft or shuttles, the Mk3 CRG-L might be for you. This cargo hold is so huge it can be used to hold a small concert, not that we at C7 condone such things.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_m3_ramp_1x: When an emergency erupted on a remote outpost in the far north, the engineers at C7 quickly converted a large cargo hold to open at the back, and a load of snacks were airdropped to the poor Kerbals in time.When they realized it could also be used on the ground, C7 knew they had a hit.
Parts/Description/cargobay_3v_nose: Why waste all that space using an empty nosecone when the revolutionary CN-375 can be filled with snacks?
Parts/Description/cargobay_4v_1x1: The CBS-500 was originally designed to haul parts and equipment. When word got out about just how many tons of snacks it can hold, sales skyrocketed.
Parts/Description/cargobay_4v_1x4: The marketing team at Sean’s Cannery brag that the CBL-500 cargo container is so big it can safely house a live kraken, if one existed, which they don't.
Parts/Description/cargobay_4v_nose: The engineering team at Sean’s Cannery cry when they see empty nosecones. They built the CN-500 cargo nose to satisfy their need to fill every spare centimeter of space.
Parts/Description/chassis_3v_truck: Built to accompany the “Bulldog” truck cab, the “Rottweiler” truck chassis is designed to make your rover building faster and easier. If you wish to spend less time building and more time exploring, then this is a good choice for you.
Parts/Description/cockpit_1v_m1_crew: Sleek and sharp, everything about the Raven screams fast. This single seat cockpit comes equipped with a built-in battery and a small reaction wheel, and is equally perfect for jets, small space planes, or cool-looking rockets.
Parts/Description/cockpit_1v_m1_inline_c: The Peregrine is designed for small, fast jets and other craft. This single seat inline cockpit comes equipped with a built-in battery and reaction wheel, and it holds a small amount of monopropellant. The not-pointy nose is a front attachment node perfect for a jet intake or small parachute.
Parts/Description/cockpit_2v_m2_crew: The Phoenix is designed to handle extreme conditions, and it is a perfect choice for large jets and space planes. This cool-looking two-seater comes equipped with a built-in battery and reaction wheel, and it holds a small amount of monopropellant. But please, do NOT catch it on fire to see if it rises from the ashes.
Parts/Description/cockpit_2v_m2_inline_c: The Osprey may look like a two-seat cockpit with the nose broken off (and it is) but hear us out. It comes equipped with a built-in battery and reaction wheel, and holds a small amount of monopropellant. And now it has a forward attachment node, so you can bolt whatever you want to the front of it.
Parts/Description/cockpit_3v_m3_aircraft: The Mk3 “Pelican” might look like a cockpit mounted on top of a large cargo hold, but… that’s pretty much what it is! Just imagine the possibilities.
Parts/Description/cockpit_3v_m3_crew: The Condor is a four-seat cockpit designed for larger shuttles and spaceplanes. It comes equipped with a built-in battery and a powerful reaction wheel. And it’s large enough to store a decent amount of monopropellant, some snacks, a few board games… and maybe a small tree.
Parts/Description/cockpit_3v_truck_crew: Big and mean best describe the “Bulldog,” the only command pod specifically designed with heavy rovers in mind. Our marketing department would like to point out it looks really cool on rockets too.
Parts/Description/connector_0v_6point: The TMP-XS is a very small multi-point connector. While it may be referred to as the “Not-Rockomax Micronode," Dinkelstein Kerman’s Construction Emporium swears there was no corporate espionage involved in its design.
Parts/Description/connector_1v_6point: Reaction to the MPC-250 multi-point connector ranged from excitement to fury when it premiered at the 3rd annual Rockets & Explosions Festival. Some claimed it was just what they needed while others raged, “Rocket parts should only be placed in one direction, up!”
Parts/Description/controlsurface_1v_proc: The LPCS-250 is a control surface for when a wing or fin just won’t do. Use it to add some more lifting surfaces to a craft, impart more control, or to just make it look cooler. Whatever the case, we can build it here at Wingit.
Parts/Description/controlsurface_2v_proc: When you need a very specific control surface at a very medium size, look to this control surface. No matter the shape or size, if you bring use a sketch, we’ll make it a reality.

The LPCS-250 is a control surface for when a wing or fin just won’t do. Use it to add some more lifting surfaces to a craft, impart more control, or to just make it look cooler. Whatever the case, we can build it here at Wingit.
Parts/Description/controlsurface_3v_proc: When you need a very specific control surface at a very medium size, look to this control surface. No matter the shape or size, if you bring use a sketch, we’ll make it a reality.
The HPCS-1000 is a control surface that can be manufactured to very specific and exact standards in a very short amount of time, and at a very reasonable price. Well, not really that reasonable.
Parts/Description/coupler_1v_inline_2poi: The TVR-200 Stack Bi-Coupler is a simple method for splitting one rocket into two - without the disastrous consequences of doing it the normal (explosive) way.
Parts/Description/coupler_1v_inline_3poi: The Stack Tricoupler! If your stack is lacking in awesomeness, this is the part for you! Just remember that this is not an explosive decoupler, much to the disappointment of the R&D team.
Parts/Description/coupler_1v_inline_4poi: What could be more awesome than a tricoupler? A quadcoupler, of course! Remember that this is not a decoupler and will not separate stages, no matter how many times you try.
Parts/Description/crewCabin: The PPD-10 is a large crew cabin. It provides seating for extra kerbal astronauts while fitting neatly into a large rocket fuselage stack. It's ideal for large-scale rescue missions for the dozens of kerbals you'll inevitably strand in the cold, bleak void of space.
Parts/Description/decoupler_0v_inline: The TD-06 is a one-sided detachment device made for very small rocket stacks or payload deployment. Accounting would like to remind the team that they are not for pranks.
Parts/Description/decoupler_1v_aerodynam: The AD-12 is a small radial decoupler designed for jets and spaceplanes. It is slanted and highly streamlined, adding a really cool look to any craft.
Parts/Description/decoupler_1v_inline: The TD-12 is a one-sided detachment device made for small rocket stacks or payloads. The arrows painted on the sides indicate which side will decouple. OMB is not financially responsible for reverse decoupler incidents.
Parts/Description/decoupler_1v_radial: The TT-38K is a radial decoupler that uses a small explosive charge to detach radial stages, and hopefully only that. It is perfect for dropping spent solid fuel boosters after they have gotten your rocket off the launchpad.
Parts/Description/decoupler_2v_aerodynam: The AD-25 is a mid-sized radial decoupler for jets and spaceplanes, used to detach spent fuel tanks. The engineers love its sleek appearance and assure us that appearance does equate to performance.
Parts/Description/decoupler_2v_inline: The TD-25 is a one-sided decoupler designed for medium rockets. It took our team three times, but the arrows are properly aligned to denote which side has the explosions.
Parts/Description/decoupler_2v_radial: The TT-38X is an extended version of the TT-38K decoupler. Because it is radially mounted, it can also be used as an interesting structural hardpoint when disengaged.
Parts/Description/decoupler_3v_inline: The TD-37 is a single-sided detachment device crafted for large rocket stacks or payloads. Equipped with several small explosive charges and warning arrows to indicate which side will detach, the TD-37 is perfect for discarding your lower stages when the time comes to say goodbye. Goodbye song optional.
Parts/Description/decoupler_3v_radial: The TT-140A is a large radial detachment device that uses an explosive charge to detach and eject whatever is connected to it safely away from your craft. OMB focus testing proved that the word "manifold" is super cool.
Parts/Description/decoupler_4v_inline: The TD-50 is a single-sided detachment device built for very large rockets. Just remember they have arrows painted on them for a reason: point them in the right direction...
Parts/Description/decoupler_4v_radial: The TT-440XL is an extra large radial decoupler for detaching large, radially attached subassemblies. Premature activation has been known to knock delivery trucks halfway across the VAB by "accident."
Parts/Description/dockingport_0v_inline: The Clamp-O-Tron Jr. is a very small docking port that will attach to a docking port of the same size. It can create an airtight seal between two crafts. While the port may have been cobbled together from a small serving hatch, it is just large enough for a Kerbal to squeeze through.
Parts/Description/dockingport_1v_inline: The Clamp-O-Tron is a small docking port designed to attach to any other docking port of the same diameter. This includes the Shielded, Inline, and Mk2 variants. It is also just large enough for a Kerbal helmet to fit through, making it a vast improvement over the Clamp-O-Tron Jr.
Parts/Description/dockingport_1v_inline_: The Clamp-O-Tron Shielded is just what the name implies, a standard docking port with a protective shield, letting it tolerate higher temperatures. Inspired by a clothes dryer door spotted during a parts scrounge, this version is much more aerodynamic than the standard Clamp-O-Tron.

The Clamp-O-Tron Inline is a small docking port built to attach to any docking port of the same diameter. The prototype came from a Clamp-O-Tron blueprint being read sideways, but it was a success. It is very aerodynamic, making it an excellent choice for small spaceplanes.
Parts/Description/dockingport_2v_inline: The Clamp-O-Tron Sr. is a heavier and sturdier docking port than its smaller counterparts, and it is a great choice for medium to large craft and stations. Maybe a couple of small trucks or buses. Just make sure the right side is pointed outward before you launch.
Parts/Description/dockingport_2v_m2_inli: Protected inside its own streamlined housing, the Mk2 Clamp-O-Tron is an excellent choice for spaceplanes. But the engineers at C7 Aerospace will never admit the inspiration was an Mk1 inline Clamp-O-Tron that got stuck inside an Mk2 cargo hold with a couple of monopropellant tanks.
Parts/Description/dockingport_3v_inline: The CC375-D is a large, all-purpose docking port that established Coop’s Connectors as a serious player in the aerospace industry. Who knew bigger was better?
Parts/Description/dockingring_4v_inline: When the call went out for an extra large docking port, it was Coop s Connectors that answered with the CC5-D. By retrofitting an old Clamp-O-Tron Sr. into the endplate of a 5 meter fuel tank, the CC engineers have crafted an attachment device capable of handling all but the most extreme situations.
Parts/Description/engine_0v_methalox_ant: If smaller is better, then micro must be magnificent! With that in mind, Jeb's Junkyard designed the LV-1 “Ant”, a micro-engine built specifically for smaller satellites and probes. It has a limited thrust but impressive ISP in vacuum. No, this is not an engine for insects.
Parts/Description/engine_0v_methalox_spa: In an attempt to stay competitive, Rockomax designed the extra small “Spark” methalox engine. There may have been a minor uprising among the engineering staff who refused to “go small,” but in the end the team designed a very powerful and efficient engine that performs especially well in a vacuum.
Parts/Description/engine_0v_methalox_spi: The LV-1R "Spider" is a variant of the "Ant" methalox micro-engine, designed for small probes and satellites. It has a limited thrust but impressive ISP in a vacuum, and it can be radially attached to almost anything. The design department recommends using multiples of 8 for aesthetic reasons.
Parts/Description/engine_0v_methalox_twi: When your lander or probe needs some extra thrust, the "Twitch" methalox engine might be just the ticket. Small and radially mounted, it can be used in any number of combinations to meet your design needs. Is it an attempt to outdo rival Kerbodyne's "Spider" engine? Absolutely not!
Parts/Description/engine_0v_methane_whit: When C7 Aerospace first proposed the "Whittle" air breathing engine, it was widely mocked as being useless in space. C7 responded, "Why fly up when you can fly sideways" and laughed their way to the bank. Years later C7 rules the skies of Kerbin, and the little "Whittle" jet engine is as popular as ever.
Parts/Description/engine_0v_monoprop_puf: The O-10 "Puff" is a unique rocket engine that uses monopropellant for fuel. Originally designed to be a large RCS thruster, it was mislabeled right before a major ad campaign. Much to Reaction Systems Ltd. surprise, the overwhelming response was "Well, it's about time!"
Parts/Description/engine_0v_xenon_dawn: The IX-6315 "Dawn" is a small Ion thruster. It was designed by D. Kerman, a brilliant theremin player, after they made a startling discovery experimenting with magnetic fields. This engine produces very little thrust, but it is amazingly efficient and has a gorgeous blue glow. What's not to like?
Parts/Description/engine_1v_hydrogen_ner: The LV-N “Nerv” is the very first nuclear-powered rocket engine. It may be an insane approach to rocket propulsion, but it boasts a staggering ISP in vacuum, making it much more efficient than conventional methalox engines. Yes, it may be a little radioactive, but more glow means more go, right?
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_dar: The T-1 "Dart" is C7 s only methalox engine, and is rather unique in its design. It has a decent amount of thrust and is reasonably efficient both in and out of an atmosphere, making it a very well-rounded engine. It also has a very short profile, which works well for landers.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_rel: The "Reliant" takes the guesswork out of the first stage of your rocket, by only having one direction of thrust. Just point it toward the planet you're trying to leave!
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_swi: The "Swivel" is a small but versatile methalox engine. It features a full 3 degrees of thrust vectoring, making it a good choice for smaller rockets. Inspired when a barbeque grill tipped over and hit a propane tank, it remains one of Jeb's Junkyard's most successful engines.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_ter: Hot off the runway, the "Terrier" fuses function and fashion. It's perfect for transporting smaller, late stages of a rocket through space. Only comes in medium.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_thu: The “Thud” is the largest radially-mounted methalox engine available. It is powerful and efficient in and out of an atmosphere, and it can be used in any number of combinations. The marketing team swears it did not earn its name from slightly “less than successful” test runs.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methalox_vec: The “Vector” is Kerbodyne’s flagship engine. It is heavier than engines like “Reliant,” and has nearly the power of a “Mainsail,” with a gimbal range over 10 degrees. This engine works great both in and out of an atmosphere, and our engineers promise their new alloys make it 99% less likely to explode.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_methane-meth: The Reactive Alternate-Propellent Intelligent Engine for Rockets is a marvel of technology that can function as an airbreathing jet engine or closed cycle rocket engine. This makes it widely popular for spaceplane designs, and hugely profitable for both C7 and Rockomax.
Parts/Description/engine_1v_turbofan_met: The J-404 “Panther” jet engine is similar in design to the “Wheesley,” but it didn't skip the gym. It has 10 degrees of thrust vectoring and an afterburner, making it capable of insane bursts of speed while also being highly maneuverable. This is one of Jeb’s favorite engines.

The J-33 "Wheesley" is the standard in Kerbal jet engine technology, and used widely in smaller commercial aircraft. It performs better in lower cruising speeds and altitudes, making it ideal for sightseeing, exploring, or seeing and exploring!
Parts/Description/engine_1v_turboramjet_: Utilizing the latest in ramjet technology, the J-X4 “Whiplash” jet engine is capable of reaching speeds far above standard jet engines. It is inefficient at sea level, but is unparalleled at higher altitudes. It's extremely useful for long range aircraft or smaller SSTOs.
Parts/Description/engine_2v_methalox_mai: The “Mainsail” is one of the most powerful methalox rocket engines available and works well on the launch pad as well as in a vacuum. It’s also one of the most popular engines on the planet, something the Rockomax sales department loves to remind their rivals at Kerbodyne whenever possible.
Parts/Description/engine_2v_methalox_poo: Rockomax’s 3rd engine, the "Poodle", may not have the thrust of its predecessors, but its efficiency in a vacuum is very impressive. It is an excellent choice for an upper stage delivery system. If this were a dog show, the "Poodle: would be a finalist for sure.
Parts/Description/engine_2v_methalox_ski: The “Skipper” is Rockomax’s second most powerful engine next to the “Mainsail,” and it is very good for intermediate stages. It is also Rockomax’s second best-selling engine next to the “Mainsail.” Our engineers guarantee it is not jealous, they hope.
Parts/Description/engine_2v_turbofan_met: The J-90 “Goliath” is a monster sized jet engine that truly lives up to its name. Its thrust far exceeds any other jet engine at low altitude while still being amazingly efficient. While this engine is strong enough to fly a large cargo plane around Kerbin, it's still susceptible to small rocks.
Parts/Description/engine_3v_hydrogen_swe: The "Super Warm Engine for Rocket Vehicles" is a gas-core nuclear engine designed for high thrust operations. It consists of five tubes attached to a structure that allows them to gimbal. Jeb swears he did not find those tubes in the spare lightbulbs box.
Parts/Description/engine_3v_methalox_lab: The “Labradoodle” is Kerbodyne’s newest engine. It does not perform well in an atmosphere, but is very efficient in vacuum, making it a great choice for upper stages. Rumor has it the Labradoodle was actually named by a safe-flying web-caster during an interview.
Parts/Description/engine_3v_methalox_mam: Kerbodyne’s “Mammoth-II” is a next generation methalox engine that combines massive power with massive size. Nothing about this engine is small.
Parts/Description/engine_3v_methalox_rhi: Like its namesake, the KR-2XL “Rhino” is a brute, and one of Kerbodyne’s largest methalox engines. It has a decent amount of power in an atmosphere, but truly shines in vacuum. With a “Rhino” you can truly charge to the stars in style.
Parts/Description/enginemount_1v_procedu: The MEM-125 offers an alternative to using one large engine: use several smaller ones! Perhaps one big engine and a few small ones combined? One small engine and a few big ones? Why not?
Parts/Description/enginemount_2v_procedu: This versatile engine mount uses the most advanced fuel flow technology, allowing the user to connect an almost infinite variety and number of engines to one craft. Use your engine mounting superpowers for good.
Parts/Description/enginemount_3v_m3: The EM-500 was designed as an engine mount for Mk3 style rockets and spaceplanes. It can withstand a tremendous amount of heat. It takes hours to cool, making it ideal for after-flight grilled cheese sandwiches!
Parts/Description/enginemount_3v_procedu: How many engines can you mount to the end of one craft? The MEM-375 is designed for just this question. Please don’t blow up the VAB finding the answer.
Parts/Description/enginemount_4v_procedu: Is it possible to surround a big Mainsail engine with a lot of little Spark engines? Using the MEM-500 Multi Engine Plate it is. Along with any other combination of engines you can think of. You are only limited by your imagination.
Parts/Description/escapesystem_1v_launch: The LES “Bottle-Rocket” is a small solid rocket booster that is attached to a command pod. In a catastrophic emergency, it can shoot a crew safely away before the worst happens. Ironically enough, while it is intended to never be used, it is Kerbodyne’s best selling product.
Parts/Description/fairing_0v_procedural: Just like its namesake, the “Littleneck” protective fairing is strong for its size and guaranteed to keep your precious components safe and sound.
Parts/Description/fairing_1v_procedural: The AE-FF125 is a protective fairing designed to keep your precious cargo safe until deployed. The CEO won the Name This Part competition.
Parts/Description/fairing_2v_procedural: The AE-FF250 “Scallop” is a protective fairing and nothing more. We at FLOOYD wish to apologize to any customers who bought it expecting something inside.
Parts/Description/fairing_3v_procedural: A large protective fairing, no amount of muscle will open this “Mussel” before it’s ready.
Parts/Description/fairing_4v_procedural: The AE-FF500 protective fairing one of FLOOYD Dynamics favorites just for the name itself: “Quahog.” Try saying it five times fast!
Parts/Description/fin_0v_procedural: While it might be their smallest product, the LAF-125 is a very adjustable aerodynamic fin. Whatever you design: small, large, shark-shaped; the crew at Wingit will custom build this fin to your exact specifications.
Parts/Description/fuelcell_0v: The FC-01 Fuel Cell consumes a minute amount of methalox to produce electricity, and it shines when solar panels will not suffice. Be warned: if you use the FC-01 to keep the lights on all night, you may find yourself without a way home in the morning.
Parts/Description/fuelcell_1v_array: The FCA-06 Fuel Cell Array combines 6 standard FC-01 fuel cells to produce electricity. It consumes a small amount of methalox, so keep an eye on your fuel levels when it is in use.
Parts/Description/fuelline_0v_external: The FTX-2 External Fuel Duct is a breakthrough for FLOOYD Dynamics in fuel transfer technology, allowing fuel to transfer between tanks. Some critics may call it a glorified firehose, others a refurbished sewage line, but it works, and made asparagus much more popular.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_inline_met: The Oscar-B is a very small methalox fuel tank made for compact satellites and probes. No one knows who Oscar B was, but the fuel tank is extremely popular.

The R-12 is a very small, toroid shaped, radially attached, external methalox fuel tank. That was hard for the Probodobodyne engineers to remember, so they called it the "Doughnut." It is designed as an alternative for small satellites, and it comes in a very stylish gold foil.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_inline_mon: The FL-R10 is a very small, inline monopropellant tank, perfect for craft requiring just a little RCS thruster boost every now and then. We’re told they make excellent kettle drums when they’re empty.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_inline_xen: After some intense discussions on how to pronounce the word “Xenon”, Probodobodyne introduced the PB-X150 Xenon gas container. This is designed for use with ion engines. While the amount may seem minute, it can provide enough fuel for a small ion probe to reach the Mun and beyond.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_m0_inline_: The JF-50 is designed to provide a small amount of methane to a jet or other airbreathing craft. When combined with a small aerodynamic decoupler, it makes an excellent under-wing drop tank. Just be very careful not to drop them on anyone, please.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_radial_met: The R4 "Dumpling" is one of the smallest fuel tanks available, designed for compact satellites and probes. It is extremely lightweight and encased in an elegant gold foil. Make sure that it is empty before using it in a late-night VAB kickball game.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_radial_mon: The Stratus-V Roundified is one of the most popular monopropellant storage tanks in the Stratus Corp inventory. These tanks are radially attached, so their positions and capacities can be used to tweak a vehicle's center of mass.

The Stratus-V Minified is the smallest and cutest monopropellant tank available. It holds a very minute amount of fuel, so it is common to see rings of them on a vehicle. Remember this is a precision made fuel storage tank, not a toy.
Parts/Description/fueltank_0v_radial_xen: The PB-X50R is a radially mounted Xenon gas container designed to provide fuel for ion engines. Small, lightweight, and stylish, one or two of these can provide enough fuel for an ion craft to reach incredible distances at a reasonable price.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_inline_hyd: The HFT-T-125 was designed to hold a small but significant amount of liquid hydrogen safely. Rumors that this tank also floats slightly off the ground when full are completely unfounded.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_inline_met: The FL-T100 is the smallest of the FL methalox fuel tanks series. It can be used for small satellites and probes, or if your rocket needs a little extra fuel, just in case you don't trust the dV calculation.
The FL-T200 is a small diameter methalox fuel tank, and is a favorite for fueling small landers. Like all the FL series tanks, it can also be radially attached, adding lots of fun building options.
The FL-T400 is a small diameter methalox fuel tank, and a good choice for upper stage assemblies. This fuel tank was designed for those craft that need just enough fuel, but not too much.
The FL-T800 is the largest of the FL series of methalox fuel tanks, and works great on upper stages or for small stand alone rockets. The FL-T800 will help fuel the way to space.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_inline_mon: Several recent advancements in plumbing have made monopropellant tanks like the FL-R25 capable of fueling any RCS thruster on a craft, no matter the location. Just watch your fuel levels, especially when docking. Jeb assures you he is not speaking from personal experience.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_inline_xen: The PB-X750 is one of the largest of the xenon gas containers available. With one or two of these impressive-looking containers, an ion engine could have enough fuel to reach Eve, Duna, or even Jool!
No one in marketing really expected there to be a demand for a xenon fuel tank this large. But if it's efficient, we'll build it!
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_m1_inline_: The JF-200 is a small methane fuel tank. The staff at C7 Aerospace vehemently deny it was originally designed using a methalox fuel tank borrowed from Jeb’s Junkyard.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_radial_met: The "Baguette" is arguably the classiest methalox fuel tank available. It was designed with satellites in mind, but it looks great on any craft. It has been nominated for a modern art award two years running.
Parts/Description/fueltank_1v_radial_mon: After years of research and development, Stratus Corp decided the best course for the future was not spheres, but cylinders. This radially attached monopropellant tank holds a moderate amount of fuel while also being quite attractive, versatile, and very cylindrical.
Parts/Description/fueltank_2v_inline_hyd: Using the latest multi-layer insulation materials, the HFT-T-250 is designed to hold your hydrogen fuel safely under all conditions. Flying into a planet is not covered under the warranty.

Unsatisfied with what the competition had to offer, Urika developed their own line of hydrogen fuel tanks. The HFT-S-250 is the smallest in the series, but far superior in every way to conventional fuel tanks, at least according to our marketing department.
Parts/Description/fueltank_2v_inline_met: The X200-8 is a medium diameter methalox fuel tank, and the shortest of the X200 series. It is an excellent choice for upper stages and landers, or if your fuel stack needs just a little extra. Despite the design, it should not be used as a trampoline.

After countless hours of intensive study, research, and nearly a metric ton of coffee and snacks, the engineers at Rockomax Conglomerate came to the unanimous conclusion that there was a need for a fuel tank twice the size of the X200-8.

Developed after one J. Kerman complained that the fuel tanks available were "way too small," the X200-32 holds a generous amount of fuel for all your fueling needs (or something like that). Rockomax hires rocket scientists, not writers.

The Jumbo-64 is Rockomax’s largest fuel tank, and it holds a considerable amount of methalox, making it a good choice for fueling any mid-sized rocket engine. The folks in marketing also promise it is much safer than anything their rival Kerbodyne manufactures (results may vary).
Parts/Description/fueltank_2v_inline_mon: The FL-R1 is designed for mid-sized stacks, and it can hold a considerable amount of monopropellant fuel. This makes it ideal for medium to large craft requiring precision docking and landing.
Parts/Description/fueltank_2v_m2_inline_: The RFT-400 is an Mk2 style tank designed to provide fuel to space planes and other cool-looking craft. It holds a decent amount of methalox and provides lift in an atmosphere, making it an ideal candidate for smaller single-stage-to-orbit vehicles.

When your ambition steers towards larger space planes, the RFT-800 is the way to go. This aerodynamic Mk2 style tank not only holds a significant amount of Methalox, it provides lift in an atmosphere. The C7 marketing department swears it can make any craft go faster.

The JFT-400 might not seem very large, but this aerodynamically-designed Mk2 style methane tank can still provide a jet engine with fuel for a considerable time. It is also popular with space planes that are intended to spend some time in an atmosphere.

The JFT-800 is C7’s best-selling Mk2 style methane fuel tank. It holds a considerable amount of methane, and also provides lift in an atmosphere. The C7 engineering staff always seems to have a new build requiring this tank.

If your space plane requires docking thrusters, then the MFT-400 is a must. This Mk2 style monopropellant tank is aerodynamically designed to provide a small amount of lift, and advanced plumbing designs allow it to provide fuel to any thruster on a craft.
Parts/Description/fueltank_3v_inline_hyd: The HFT-T-375 is an extended version of the HFT-S-375 fuel tank, and uses the latest in cryogenic technology to keep your hydrogen fuel liquified and stable. It also works great for flash freezing snacks! Be careful not to waste too much because, well, it’s fuel. You probably need it.

When demand for more advanced engines and fuel tanks grew, Urika Inc. responded with the HFT-S-375. It is capable of holding much more than the HFT-S-250 and is just as beautiful. Just look at all that gold foil!
Parts/Description/fueltank_3v_inline_met: The S3-3600 is the shortest of the S3 series, but it still holds a considerable amount of methalox. Originally designed for test environments, it went into full production as soon as the CEO heard rumors that Rockomax was manufacturing their own short fuel tanks.
The S3-7200 is Kerbodyne’s best selling fuel tank. It was originally designed for use with Kerbodyne’s Rhino engine. It holds twice as much as the S3-3600 while guaranteeing to be no more explosive.

Yes, the S3-14400 is one of the largest fuel tanks available. Yes, it holds an amazing amount of highly explosive methalox fuel. Yes, it could quite probably take out half the VAB if one accidentally exploded. Yes… what was the question again?
Parts/Description/fueltank_3v_inline_mon: When the call went out for larger and larger RCS systems, the R&D team at Jeb’s Junkyard welded several Stratus-V Roundified monopropellant tanks into an empty storage container and introduced it as the FL-R100. Copyright infringement litigation with Stratus Corporation is ongoing.
Parts/Description/fueltank_3v_m3_inline_: The RFT-2500 is a methalox fuel tank designed for shuttles and other Mk3 style craft. It is the shortest of the series, but still holds a considerable amount of fuel.
The RFT-5000 is designed to provide Methalox to Mk3 style craft such as shuttles and large single-stage-to-orbit craft. When your fuel needs are slightly less than ludicrous, this tank is for you.
The RFT-10000 is the largest Mk3 style methalox tank available. C7’s engineers also boast it has much higher crash tolerance than any of the fuel tanks that Kerbodyne or Rockomax manufacture.

The smallest of the series, the JFT-2500 holds an impressive amount of methane fuel. It is useful for large jets and other Mk3 craft. This tank works especially well when placed on either side of a large cargo hold to keep things in balance.

The JFT-5000 is one of C7’s most popular fuel tanks, designed to provide huge amounts of methane fuel to any large jet or other Mk3 style craft. It is also a great choice for large single-stage-to-orbit craft that need to fly in an atmosphere.
The JFT-10000 is the largest methane fuel tank commercially available anywhere. If you want to build an aircraft that can circumnavigate the globe, it all starts here.

The MFT-1000 is a high-tech monopropellant fuel delivery system designed to accommodate Mk3 craft. Using the newest plumbing technology, it can deliver fuel to any thruster on a craft. When your reaction wheels aren't reacting enough, try RCS and this tank.
Parts/Description/fueltank_4v_inline_hyd: The HFT-T-500 is one of the largest liquid hydrogen tanks in Urika’s inventory, and represents the latest and greatest in fuel storage technology. The CEO was so proud of it that they had one especially built in their front yard as an ornament.

Large, complex, gorgeous, the HFT-S-500 is all that and more. This extra large, extra attractive fuel tank holds a stunning amount of hydrogen rocket fuel, and it is guaranteed to make any ship look good.
Parts/Description/fueltank_4v_inline_met: In an attempt to bury the competition, Kerbodyne designed the S4 series methalox fuel tanks. Even this short S4-6400 holds a huge amount of fuel for all your rocketry needs. Hopefully, it sent rival Rockomax back to the drawing board.

When critics mocked the S4-6400 for being “ridiculously huge," Kerbodyne quietly responded by doubling its size with the S4-12800 methalox fuel tank. Now your “ridiculously huge” spacecraft can get even bigger. Have fun!
Larger than most surface holding tanks, the S4-25600 carries a massive amount of methalox rocket fuel. On its own or atop a large rocket stack, the S4-25600 is guaranteed to be reasonably safe.

This is it, the largest methalox fuel tank available and the pride of the Kerbodyne inventory: the S4-51200. Wildly over-engineered and over-budget, it is designed for those that over-dream the biggest rockets ever.
Parts/Description/fueltank_4v_radial_mon: When Stratus Corp began designing their extra large radial monopropellant tank, the team was both thrilled and horrified. They immediately agreed to name this massive construct after their favorite monster movie: “The Embiggened.”
Parts/Description/fuselage_1v_m1_structu: The SF-125 is not a high strength, ultra-light, aerodynamic tube. It’s a high strength, ultra-light, aerodynamic structural fuselage. The engineers at C7 Aerospace insist there's a huge difference.
Parts/Description/generator_0v_thermoele: Heavy for its size, the PB-NUK generates a small but steady amount of electricity without consuming any resources, making it perfect for nighttime or dark environments. While it also produces a small amount of heat, we highly advise against using it for a snack warmer.
Parts/Description/generator_1v_fission_r: Once it’s activated, this reactor puts out a steady flow of electricity for many years. The inventor was inspired to pursue a conical form after burning her tongue on a rolled crepe cone. The pointy end is especially hot and a wee bit radioactive.
Parts/Description/generator_3v_thermoele: The RTG-500 is a second generation radioisotope thermoelectric generator capable of generating a steady flow of electricity for many years. It also produces a moderate amount of heat, so refrain from standing near one too long. It's not like you’ll start to glow.
Parts/Description/heatshield_0v: Originally designed to be a high end hibachi grill, the HS-01T turned out to be a fantastic little heat shield. What you do with it after you land is up to you.
Parts/Description/heatshield_1v: The team at O.M.B Demolitions were a skeptical working on heat shields, but they soon learned that superheating a part to insane temperatures and not having them explode was almost as much fun as blowing them up. Almost.
Parts/Description/heatshield_2v: The HS-250 combines the latest high-tensile alloys combined with a heaping amount of <top-secret heat absorbing ingredient> to ensure your craft stays cool and safe during re-entry.
Parts/Description/heatshield_2v_inflatab: The HS-I is a unique inflatable heat shield, and one of O.M.B. Demolition’s best sellers. It is large enough to protect even extra large craft during re-entry, and it doubles as a bouncy house after landing! What’s not to like?
Parts/Description/heatshield_3v: The HS-375 large heat shield may resemble a children's swimming pool, but we can assure you that a great amount of time and energy went into its design. The R&D team only used it for swimming on weekends.
Parts/Description/heatshield_4v: The HS-500 is an extra large heat shield that uses an extra amount of high-tensile alloys combined with an extra amount of <top-secret heat absorbing ingredient> to keep you extra safe during extra extremes of re-entry. Did we mention it is extra stylish?
Parts/Description/heatshield_4v_inflatab: The HS-I is a unique inflatable heat shield, and one of O.M.B. Demolition’s best sellers. It is large enough to protect even extra large craft during re-entry, and it doubles as a bouncy house after landing! What’s not to like?
Parts/Description/ibeam_1v_1x5: The M-Beam 200 Pocket Edition is a small I-beam that can be used in a variety of ways, from construction to emergency seating arrangements. It’s very heavy, so don’t drop it on your foot.
Parts/Description/ibeam_2v_1x10: The M-Beam 200 is a finely crafted engineering marvel. Please don’t treat it like it’s just a big hunk of metal.
Parts/Description/ibeam_2v_2x3: After much time and effort, the R&D team at Dinkelstein Kerman’s Construction Emporium decided the best option for the future was to make their wildly successful M-Beam 200 twice as long!
Parts/Description/intake_0v_circular: A must for air-breathing engines, C7’s Small Circular Intake will provide all the air a small jet engine requires. Atmosphere not included.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_circular: The Circular Intake can provide air to any turbine style jet engine available. It can also suck the snacks right out of your lunchbox and send them right through your engine for a nutritious snack smoothie!
Parts/Description/intake_1v_m1_adjustabl: The Adjustable Ramp Intake is similar to C7’s Circular Intake, but it is more efficient. The engineers at C7 would like to point out it looks cooler than the standard circular intake while being only slightly more expensive.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_m1_nacelle_m: The Engine Nacelle comes equipped with a small intake along with a built-in fuel reserve, making it a very practical option for smaller aircraft. Never mind the burn marks, marketing assures us those are there to make it look fast.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_m1_precooler: Similar to the Engine Nacelle, the Engine Pre-cooler has an intake and holds a small amount of fuel. The Pre-Cooler uses the most advanced alloys to channel heat away from your engines, especially useful when using the inferior engines of our competitors.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_m1_shockcone: A shocking breakthrough in intake technology (see what we did there?), the Shock Cone Intake is designed to provide air to turbine style engines while also reducing drag at supersonic speeds. It is a great choice for smaller high-speed jets and SSTOs.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_m1_supersoni: The Mk1 Diverterless Supersonic Intake is the next step in structural intake technology, and it comes equipped with both a high-speed intake and a built-in fuel reserve. This is a great option for those who don’t want an ugly intake on the front of their private jet.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_radial: The XM-G50 uses the most advanced air duct technology available, allowing it to be radially attached almost anywhere on an aircraft and provide a steady flow of air to the engines. C7 vehemently denies the air duct tech was “borrowed” from FLOOYD Dynamics Research Labs.
Parts/Description/intake_1v_ramp_radial_: The Adjustable Ramp Intake is made for those that cannot pump enough air into their high performance jets and SSTOs. It was also designed to look streamlined and fast. If it looks fast, then it must be fast, right?
Parts/Description/junction_0v_square: The STJ-625 is an extremely versatile square junction truss, and the cornerstone product of Bob’s Girders. It is literally the cornerstone of our snack vending machine in the main office.
Parts/Description/junction_0v_square_0-3: A tiny truss junction, the STJ-3125 was voted “Most significant advance in Truss technology since the SRT-XS-XXS resizing truss” by In Truss we Trust Quarterly Journal.
Parts/Description/junction_1v_circular: The CTJ-125 is designed to attach as many as six other circular struts. It is also just large enough to crawl inside and roll around.
Parts/Description/junction_1v_square: A lot of time and research went into crafting the STJ-125 truss junction. Despite being the square version of the CTJ-125, it took three times as long to develop.
Parts/Description/junction_2v_circular: The CTJ-250 can attach as many as 6 other circular trusses, resizers, or even other junctions. Attach whatever you want, you are only limited by your imagination and physics. Mostly physics.
Parts/Description/junction_2v_square: This large square truss junction boasts over 300 precision welding points, nearly 100 titanium bolts, and 500 injured fingers.
Parts/Description/junction_3v_circular: The CTJ-375 is extremely versatile and can be used to attach up to six other trusses or truss-shaped objects. Just think how handy this will be for building space stations!
Parts/Description/junction_3v_square: The STJ-375 truss junction is large and square and in dire need of a catchy jingle.
Parts/Description/junction_4v_circular: The CTJ-500 circular truss junction is extremely popular for constructing both orbital platforms and very large craft. Complementary pamphlet “1001 Fun Truss Ideas” included free of charge.
Parts/Description/junction_4v_square: This junction is designed to attach as many as 6 other trusses or other parts. Some on the engineering team is still arguing that it’s been called a “Square Truss Junction” when it is, in fact, a cube.
Parts/Description/ladder_0v_fixed_pegasu: The "Pegasus 1" Advanced Mobility Enhancer is a very high tech device intended to assist in a kerbals upward mobility needs. Do not call it a ladder. Rokea will cancel our contract in a split second if they hear you.
Parts/Description/ladder_1v_telescoping_: The "Kelus" Telescopic Mobility Enhancer is a breakthrough in upward, and more importantly downward, mobility requirements for Kerbals to survive and explore space properly. It can also be hidden away when not in use!
Parts/Description/ladder_2v_telescoping_: Building on their amazing "Kelus" mobility technology, Rokea Inc. designed the "Kelus Long", guaranteed to improve a Kerbals vertical mobility as much as 3-4 meters!
Parts/Description/ladder_3v_telescoping_: It is hard to put into words how proud the team at Rokea Inc. are of the new "Bobus" Mobility Enhancer. This incredible device not only improves a Kerbal's vertical mobility, they can also be connected to extend that mobility as far as one wishes! You are bringing Kerbals along, right?
Parts/Description/landinggear_0v_steerab: While it is not retractable, the LY-05 is still a very popular landing gear for small aircraft. It also makes a fantastic unicycle wheel, despite LightYear’s best attempts to deny it.
Parts/Description/landinggear_1v: Although it may look fragile, the LY-10 landing gear is incredibly tough, designed for both small aircraft and SSTOs. Built of the finest alloys, it can handle the extremes of Kerbin reentry. Make sure to retract them after takeoff unless you want some impromptu air brakes.
Parts/Description/landinggear_1v_fixed: Designed primarily for ultra-light aircraft, the LY-01 landing gear provides both strength and stability. LightYear insists it is not a fancy training wheel for rookie pilots.
Parts/Description/landinggear_2v: After several intense months of research into how to improve the LY-10 landing gear, the crew at LightYear came to the brilliant conclusion: add a second tire! Introducing the LY-35, designed for medium aircraft and spaceplanes, and featuring not one, but two-heavy duty tires.
Parts/Description/landinggear_3v: The LY-60 landing gear is designed for larger aircraft and space planes. It has excellent ground clearance, four deluxe tires, and very cool looking spots and brake lights! It helps to see when you’re landing at night, am I right?
Parts/Description/landinggear_4v: Huge, tough, durable, the LY-99 series landing gear is all that and more. This high strength landing system is built to handle the largest airliners and space planes without blowing out. Don’t forget to extend them before landing, because legal makes sure we don't.
Parts/Description/landingleg_0v: Small and lightweight, the “Bandicoot” is a great landing leg for diminutive landers and other small craft. They also make really fun stilts, but don’t let management catch you playing with them.
Parts/Description/landingleg_1v: Lightweight yet strong, the "Wallaroo" is one of MPEG’s most popular landing legs. It is designed mostly for exploratory surface probes, but it is bouncy enough to be great fun for crewed landers.
Parts/Description/landingleg_2v: Big and burly, the “Wombat” is designed for heavier landers and other craft. By utilizing a combination of heavy duty shock absorbers with ultra-strong bungee cords, the “Wombat” is sure to provide a soft landing every time.
Parts/Description/landingleg_3v: Arguably the most handsome of the landing legs, the “Wallaby” is both strong and durable, and comes in its own stylish protective casing. The next Kerbal we catch hiding snacks inside one is getting a serious time-out. We’re talking at least 10-15 minutes!
Parts/Description/launchclamp_3v_ground: The team at O.M.B. wish to remind everyone that there is nothing more embarrassing than having your brand-new rocket tip over on the launch pad. Utilizing the most advanced stability enhancing technology, the TT18-A guarantees your rocket will stay upright until launch. After launch is up to you.
Parts/Description/light_0v_broad: As its name suggests, the Broad Range Photonic Generation System can cast a steady stream of photonic energy over a wider area but at less intensity. Use these when you want a softer, more ambient glow to your craft.
Parts/Description/light_0v_bulb: This ingenious device includes a transparent silicon casing enclosing a super heated filament in a perfect vacuum, generating a steady stream of photonic energy. Rokea insists it is never ever to be called a light bulb. Ever.
Parts/Description/light_0v_dome: Another of Rokea’s amazing devices, the Advanced Overhead Photonic Generation System supplies a steady and reliable stream of photonic energy in a downward direction, perfect for illuminating the interior of your craft. It makes a great nightlight.
Parts/Description/light_0v_navigation: To assist in your craft’s navigational requirements, Rokea Inc. has modified their popular photonic generator technology to fit onto a ship’s wing, tail, or just about anywhere you want to put one. Auto-blinky feature included free of charge.
Parts/Description/light_0v_spot: This device is capable of emitting a vast quantity of photons in a specific direction, and thereby illuminating whatever is in its path. Try not to look at it while it's active.
Parts/Description/light_0v_spot_narrow: The Focused Photonic Generation System can emit a highly concentrated beam of photonic energy in a specific direction for a considerable distance. The engineers really wanted to build a laser, and this was as far as legal allowed.
Parts/Description/light_0v_strip: The Two-Dimensional Photonic Generation System is a fascinating variation of Rokea’s Photonic technology and can be used in a variety of useful ways. They also make gorgeous decorations for lighting up any craft.
Parts/Description/nosecone_0v: The TNC-01 is a tiny aerodynamic nose cone, and the only one C7 Aerospace designed before deciding nose cones were boring and aerodynamic intakes were rad.
Parts/Description/nosecone_1v_advanced_c: Is that pesky atmosphere getting in the way of your rocket? Not anymore! The Goliath National Products Mk3A nose cone is designed to cut through the air like butter and get you to space with as little effort as possible.
Parts/Description/nosecone_1v_advanced_r: The Mk3B slanted nose cone is an offset version of Goliath National Products’s Mk3A. It was originally marked as a QA reject, until a young technician spun it around so it lined flush with the intended craft. They earned themselves quite a bonus in snacks.
Parts/Description/nosecone_1v_hemisphere: The Mk5H is shorter and rounder than its counterparts but no less effective at shoving that annoying atmosphere aside during flight.
Parts/Description/nosecone_2v_mk2: The Mk2-HNC isn’t just your average nose cone. Sleek, sharp, but surprisingly strong, everything about this nose cone screams fast, faster, fastest.
Parts/Description/nosecone_2v_protective: Drag becoming a real drag? Not anymore. Introducing the Mk7A nose cone, now with even less drag than previous models.
Parts/Description/nosecone_3v: Intended for large, heavy craft, the Mk12A Nose Cone is perfect for reducing drag, improving efficiency, and increasing sleekatude, a real stat.
Parts/Description/nosecone_4v: The Mk16A is one of the largest protective nose cones on the market. Marketing would like us to remind everyone that nose cones are usually the first part of any rocket to reach space. We’re not sure why that’s important, but there it is.
Parts/Description/panel_0v_square: Strong and lightweight, the SP-S06 structural panel is made for a variety of uses ranging from custom construction down to balancing one on a Micronode to make a nifty snack table. (Dinkelstein Multi-Point Connector sold separately)
Parts/Description/panel_0v_triangle_equi: The SP-T06 is a very small equilateral triangle shaped structural panel that is made to be used for just about anything involving a triangle. Cones made from these parts should not be used as replacement nose cones.
Parts/Description/panel_0v_triangle_righ: The SP-R06 is a right triangle structural panel design to match the SP-S06. Buy it because it’s the right thing to do. Geometry humor is funny, right?
Parts/Description/panel_1v_square: When you feel the need to build something from scratch, the SP-S12 structural panel might be the ticket. Small and strong, it can be used to create just about anything an aspiring engineer could ask for. Buy now while they’re on-sale! Sale dates subject to change.
Parts/Description/panel_1v_triangle_equi: Much time and effort went into designing the SP-T12. Dinkelstein QA absolutely guarantees it is perfect to a tenth of a degree, and that's precision you can count on.
Parts/Description/panel_1v_triangle_righ: The SP-R12 right triangle structural panel is just that, a structural panel in the shape of a right triangle. Yes, it is technically half the size of a SP-S12 square panel. No, it is not half the cost.
Parts/Description/panel_2v_square: The SP-S25 Structural panel is twice the size and four times the squareness of the SP-S12! We’re not entirely sure what that means, but focus groups liked the sound of it.
Parts/Description/panel_2v_triangle_equi: The SP-T25 is not just a triangle shaped piece of plywood covered in gold mylar, it is a marvel of engineering technology! Years of time, effort and snacks went into its design, so please don't give it to children to trace triangles.
Parts/Description/panel_2v_triangle_righ: While it might not be one of Dinkelstein Construction Emporium’s best sellers, the SP-R25 still fills an important role in space craft construction. Shipping is free when buying in bulk!
Parts/Description/parachute_0v: What goes up must come down, and the team at Jeb’s Junkyard were one of the very first to recognize that objects can come down very, very fast. With this in mind they devised the Mk16, guaranteed to defy gravity unless deployed too soon or too late.
Parts/Description/parachute_0v_radial_dr: After countless hours of brainstorming how to keep their Mk16 parachutes from ripping at high speeds, the team at Jeb’s Junkyard came up with a brilliant idea: give the parachute a parachute! The Mk12-R drogue parachute is the result, and it is now the standard way to slow your craft safely.
Parts/Description/parachute_1v: The Mk16-XL is a variation of the standard Mk16, but designed to fit onto the nose of a capsule or craft. For best results, use it in an atmosphere. Jeb’s Junkyard is not responsible for non-atmospheric related part failures.
Parts/Description/parachute_1v_drogue: The Mk25 is an end-mounted, high-strength drogue parachute. It will not prevent you from splattering into Kerbin like a bug, but it will slow you down enough to deploy your standard parachute safely.
Parts/Description/parachute_1v_radial: The Mk16-R is a large, radial-mounted parachute designed to slow a craft to safe enough speeds to land safely. If you happen to land near some trees, they make nifty hammocks.
Parts/Description/pod_1v_conical_crew: The Mk1 “Tin Can” single-seat command pod is perfect for smaller rockets and other craft. It has a small battery, monopropellant storage, and a built-in reaction wheel. It is guaranteed to keep your pilot and their snacks safe. Just remember to pack a toothbrush for Val.
Parts/Description/pod_1v_lander_crew: The Mk1 "Explorer" is a single-seat lander can designed for landing on strange new grounds. It is very lightweight but packs the necessary features: a limited battery, monopropellant storage, and a small reaction wheel.
Parts/Description/pod_2v_conical_crew: The rounded shape of the Mk1-3 "Gumball" may remind Jeb of his favorite snack, but this is no softy. It is equipped with a sizable battery and monopropellant storage. It boasts a powerful reaction wheel capable of stabilizing even large craft.
Parts/Description/pod_2v_cupola_crew: The PPD-12 "Sightseer" is a command pod with a view. It is equipped with a small battery, monopropellant storage, and a small reaction wheel. The hexagonal windows command a magnificent view. The only downside is it has only one seat: please remember to share.
Parts/Description/pod_2v_lander_crew: The Mk2 "Tuna Can" is a cozy two-seat lander can designed to transport a pilot and crew to the surface of any body they wish to explore. Lightweight in design, it comes equipped with a small battery, monopropellant storage, and a built-in reaction wheel. Just don’t forget the snacks.
Parts/Description/pod_3v_conical_crew: Originally called the Cockpit-plus-two, the 5-seat “Cockatoo” is a second-generation command pod that provides both safety and comfort. It is rumored to have enough room to pack several days of emergency snack rations and board games.
Parts/Description/pod_3v_lander_crew: Is the Mk3-L one of the best lander cans available? Quite possibly. Was it designed with 4 seats just to get Jeb, Val, Bob & Bill to stop arguing over who got to go down on a landing? Absolutely!!!
Parts/Description/probe_0v_hexagonal_ele: The HECS is a heavily insulated, autonomous remote guidance unit designed for small satellites and probes. It comes equipped with a small internal battery, antenna, and a reaction wheel. Ensure your designs only need 6 attachment sides before manufacturing.
Parts/Description/probe_0v_octagonal_ele: The OKTO2 is a micro-sized, autonomous remote guidance unit. It is extremely lightweight has a very limited battery supply and a miniature internal reaction wheel. While it might look like a toy, please refrain from throwing expensive fun probes.

The OKTO is a heavily insulated, autonomous remote guidance unit designed for small satellites and probes. It comes equipped with a small battery and antenna. While it has a less powerful reaction wheel than the HECS, it has 8 smooth, shiny attachment surfaces.
Parts/Description/probe_0v_rectangular_e: The QBE is an autonomous remote guidance unit designed for smaller satellites and probes. It is extremely lightweight, and it is equipped with a very small battery and micro reaction wheel. Perfect for cube enthusiasts.
Parts/Description/probe_0v_spherical_ele: The Stayputnik Remote Guidance Unit (or RGU) provides the ultimate crew safety feature: no crew! The Stayputnik has a very small battery and a tiny internal reaction wheel. If you're missing the Kerbal touch, attach a couple of lights for eyes.
Parts/Description/probe_1v_disk_electric: The RC-001S is an autonomous remote guidance unit with a small, thin profile. Equipped with an internal battery and built-in reaction wheel, it is an excellent choice for returning boosters to the surface. Theories that there is a pilot inside are wholly unfounded.
Parts/Description/probe_1v_hexagonal_ele: The HECS2 is an autonomous remote guidance unit designed for large satellites and probes. It is larger and heavier than the HECS, holding an internal impressive battery and a powerful reaction wheel capable of keeping even the largest scanners stable.
Parts/Description/probe_1v_rover_electri: The RC-R "RoveMate" is a remote guidance unit designed for rovers. Low and flat, it is perfectly shaped to fit a variety of wheels. It is also wide enough to accommodate a couple of command chairs. There is no reaction wheel, so avoid those sharp turns on the mare.
Parts/Description/probe_2v_disk_electric: The RC-L01 is a large autonomous remote guidance unit. It has a sizable battery and built-in reaction wheel. The low profile is excellent for safely returning boosters and Kerbals too scared to continue.
Parts/Description/probe_2v_m2_electricit: The Mk2-DC is an autonomous remote guidance drone core, designed specifically for Mk2 style jets and spaceplanes. When your pilot needs to step back for a snack, you can trust the Mk2-DC to keep your craft flying safe.
Parts/Description/probe_3v_disk_electric: Another of STEADLER’s fine robotic guidance systems, the RC-HL02 is designed for controlling large craft in even the most difficult condition: nap time.
Parts/Description/probe_4v_disk_electric: As rockets get larger and larger, STEADLER is ready with an even larger remote guidance system. The AI can get a little snarky at times, but her heart is in the right place, on a server.
Parts/Description/rcs_0v_block_monoprop: In cooperation with Reactions Systems limited, the R&D team at STEADLER Engineering Corps. assembled four Place-Anywhere 7 thrusters into a single container and introduced the RV-105 Thruster Block. This should make docking easier and result in fewer broken solar panels.
Parts/Description/rcs_0v_linear_methalox: After Reaction Systems mis-labeled their “Puff” monopropellant thruster as an engine, and it sold off the shelves, they decided to market their VR-N1ER methalox micro-engine as a powerful all-purpose thruster. To marketing's delight, it worked!
Parts/Description/rcs_0v_linear_monoprop: Reaction Systems Ltd. likes to make the argument that the Place-Anywhere 7 was the very first rocket in existence. While other manufacturers might dispute this, it is still widely used to this day as an all-purpose thruster.
Parts/Description/resizer_0v_square_0v-0: A tiny resizing truss, the SRT-XS-XXS was voted “Most significant advance in Truss technology since the STJ-3125 truss junction” by “Truss-R-Us” magazine.
Parts/Description/resizer_1v_square_1v-0: Specifically designed to attach a tiny square truss to a slightly less tiny truss.
Parts/Description/resizer_2v_circular_2v: A circular resizing truss for all your resizing needs. Use several and make a long, thin truss cone. We’re not sure why you’d want one, but the option is available.
Parts/Description/resizer_2v_square_2v-1: The engineering team informs us that this resizing truss is classic example of a pyramidal frustum made functional. Marketing is still trying to figure out what all of that means.
Parts/Description/resizer_3v_circular_3v: This resizing truss not only attaches a medium circular truss to a large one, it can also be used in reverse to attach a large circular truss to a medium one! How hi-tech is that?
Parts/Description/resizer_3v_square_3v-2: A vast amount of research went into the study of three-dimensional isosceles trapezoidal structures to come up with this. Whatever that means, marketing guarantees it’s a pretty cool resizing truss.
Parts/Description/resizer_4v_circular_4v: This resizing truss is really large and really circular and that's really it.
The definition of this part is a “frustum of a right cone.” Marketing abandoned using that because they just could not find a way to make it sound cool.
Parts/Description/resizer_4v_square_4v-2: This may have been the accidental product of an engineer reading the blueprints without their glasses, but it went on to be a very successful resizing truss.
Parts/Description/resizer_4v_square_4v-3: Much thought and effort went into making this resizing truss as large and square as possible.
Parts/Description/seat_0v_external_crew: The EAS-1 External Command Seat is designed for rovers, built to be lightweight and durable. With an all-metal design, it earned the inglorious nickname “Grumble Seat.” Daredevils can attach one to the side of a rocket and enjoy the ride.
Parts/Description/separator_0v_inline: The TS-06 is designed to eject anything on both sides, making it a perfect choice for delivering satellites and probes to their final destinations. It uses a tiny amount of explosives, but trust us, the TS-06 is the perfect solution for any separation anxieties you may have.
Parts/Description/separator_1v_inline: The TS-12 is a separator designed to jettison whatever is attached to both sides of it, and perfect for small multi-stage craft. It is armed with several explosive bolts to safely eject anything attached. It’s also one of Jeb’s favorite parts, because all explosions are fun.
Parts/Description/separator_2v_inline: The TS-25 separator has a small amount of explosive to safely eject anything on both sides, making it perfect for medium sized, multi-stage rockets. How fun is it to split your rocket in half, using explosives, on purpose!
Parts/Description/separator_3v_inline: When the time comes to bid your lower stage farewell, the TS-37 is a good choice. The TS-37 is a large separator that will eject anything attached to both sides, including Kerbals. Handle it with care.
Parts/Description/separator_4v_inline: The TS-50 is a very large separator that explodes to eject anything attached to both sides, used by very large, multi-stage craft. Do not point either end at anyone or anything.
Parts/Description/solararray_0v_flat: The OX-STAT uses the photon energy of nearby stars to create electricity. It is very lightweight, but they must be manually moved to face the star you are nearest to for maximum efficiency. It is also quite stylish, so if you decorate your ship with some, then more power to you.
Parts/Description/solararray_1v_1x6: The OX-4L is a small, extendable 1x6 photovoltaic array designed to create electricity using the photon energy of nearby stars. It is extremely lightweight and fragile and cannot be retracted once deployed. Use it outside of an atmosphere and as far away from clumsy kerbals as possible.
Parts/Description/solararray_1v_3x2: The OX-4W 3x2 photovoltaic array uses the photon energy of nearby stars to generate electricity. It is very lightweight, fragile, and cannot be retracted once deployed. Usage inside an atmosphere is not recommended unless you like expensive kites.
Parts/Description/solararray_1v_circular: The OX-10C is a medium-sized circular photovoltaic array that uses photon energy to generate electricity. It is self tracking and boasts an improved capacity. It also reminds Val of a giant lollipop, making it one of her personal favorites.

The SP-10C is a medium sized circular photovoltaic array. It comes with a protective shroud, and that can be retracted in any kind of adverse situation. This cool-looking array is excellent for craft that may have to re-enter an atmosphere.
Parts/Description/solararray_1v_flat: The OX-STAT-XL is a large photovoltaic panel designed to create electricity using the photon energy of nearby stars. These panels cannot rack, and so they must manually positioned to face the star. The Probodobodyne sales department also recommends placing as many as you can.
Parts/Description/solararray_1v_shielded: The SP-4L is a small photovoltaic array that generates electricity using the photon energy of any nearby stars. It comes in a nifty protective shroud, and it can be retracted in dangerous situations. We do not guarantee its safety if you EVA into one.

The SP-4W is a small photovoltaic array that uses photon energy to create electricity. The SP-4W is similar to the OX-4W, but comes with a protective shroud that is both practical and stylish, making it an ideal choice for space planes and other craft that face the extremes of re-entry.
Parts/Description/solararray_2v_accordio: The Gigantor is the one of the largest photovoltaic array available, designed for colonies and large craft. It is fully retractable and self-tracking. If you bump into one, you will hear an impressive amount of yelling from the engineers.
